		<a name="top" id="top"></a>
		<div id="siteNotice"><script type='text/javascript'>if (wgNotice != '') document.writeln(wgNotice);</script></div>		<h1 id="firstHeading" class="firstHeading">Process calculus</h1>
		<div id="bodyContent">
			<h3 id="siteSub">From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia</h3>
			<div id="contentSub"></div>
									<div id="jump-to-nav">Jump to: <a href="#column-one">navigation</a>, <a href="#searchInput">search</a></div>			<!-- start content -->
			<p>In <a href="/wiki/Computer_science" title="Computer science">computer science</a>, the <b>process calculi</b> (or <b>process algebras</b>) are a diverse family of related approaches to formally modelling <a href="/wiki/Concurrent_system" title="Concurrent system" class="mw-redirect">concurrent systems</a>. Process calculi provide a tool for the high-level description of interactions, communications, and synchronizations between a collection of independent agents or processes. They also provide <a href="/wiki/Algebra" title="Algebra">algebraic</a> laws that allow process descriptions to be manipulated and analyzed, and permit formal reasoning about equivalences between processes (e.g., using <a href="/wiki/Bisimulation" title="Bisimulation">bisimulation</a>). Leading examples of process calculi include <a href="/wiki/Communicating_Sequential_Processes" title="Communicating Sequential Processes" class="mw-redirect">CSP</a>, <a href="/wiki/Calculus_of_Communicating_Systems" title="Calculus of Communicating Systems" class="mw-redirect">CCS</a>, <a href="/wiki/Algebra_of_Communicating_Processes" title="Algebra of Communicating Processes">ACP</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Language_Of_Temporal_Ordering_Specification" title="Language Of Temporal Ordering Specification">LOTOS</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-baeten2004_0-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-baeten2004-0" title=""><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup> More recent additions to the family include the <a href="/wiki/Pi-calculus" title="Pi-calculus">π-calculus</a>, the <a href="/wiki/Ambient_calculus" title="Ambient calculus">ambient calculus</a>, <a href="/wiki/PEPA" title="PEPA">PEPA</a> and the <a href="/w/index.php?title=Fusion_calculus&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="Fusion calculus (page does not exist)">fusion calculus</a>.</p>
